<Layout title="When Is a Property Sale Unconditional in Queensland? A Seller's Guide | Daniel Gierach Property" description="What contract conditions mean for Queensland sellers, when your sale goes unconditional, what you can and cannot do during the conditional period, and what happens if a buyer exits before conditions are satisfied." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When does a property sale go unconditional in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A property sale in Queensland goes unconditional when all conditions in the contract have been either satisfied or waived by the party they protect. The most common conditions are finance approval and building and pest inspection. Once both conditions are satisfied or waived, the contract becomes unconditional and neither party can exit without being in breach. For most residential sales in Brisbane, contracts go unconditional somewhere between 14 and 21 days after exchange, depending on the agreed finance and inspection periods."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a buyer pull out of a Queensland property contract before going unconditional?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. A buyer can exit a Queensland property contract before it goes unconditional if they are doing so under a contract condition. If the finance condition has not been satisfied by the due date, the buyer can terminate under that clause and their deposit is returned. The same applies to a building and pest inspection condition, though the grounds for termination under that clause are narrower than many buyers assume. Once conditions are satisfied or waived, the buyer cannot exit without being in breach of contract and at risk of losing their deposit."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens to the deposit if a buyer exits before going unconditional?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If a buyer terminates a Queensland property contract under a valid contract condition, the deposit is returned to the buyer in full. The seller cannot retain the deposit in that circumstance because the buyer is exercising a contractual right to exit, not breaching the contract. If a buyer attempts to exit after the contract has gone unconditional, the seller may be entitled to retain the deposit and potentially pursue further damages, depending on the contract terms and legal advice."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

