      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        When Is a Property Sale Unconditional in Queensland?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Going unconditional is the moment a sale becomes binding on both parties. Here is what sellers need to understand about contract conditions, the timeline, and what can happen before you get there.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>For sellers in Queensland, the moment a contract goes unconditional is the most significant milestone in the entire sale process. Before that point, the sale can still unravel. After it, both parties are bound, the buyer cannot exit without breaching the contract, and settlement is a matter of administration rather than risk. Understanding what conditions are, how they work, and what actually happens during the conditional period is essential knowledge for any Queensland property seller.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What contract conditions are</h2>
      <p>A contract condition is a clause that allows one party (usually the buyer) to exit the contract if a specified event does not occur or a specified requirement is not met within a defined timeframe. Conditions are there to protect a party from being locked into a legally binding contract before they have had the opportunity to verify something material to their decision.</p>

      <p>The two conditions that appear in the overwhelming majority of Brisbane residential property contracts are the finance condition and the building and pest inspection condition. A finance condition allows the buyer to exit if they are unable to obtain finance approval from their lender within the agreed period. A building and pest inspection condition allows the buyer to exit if the inspection reveals issues that meet the threshold specified in the contract, typically "unsatisfactory to the buyer" under the standard Queensland contract wording, though this threshold is interpreted more narrowly than many buyers assume.</p>

      <p>Some contracts also include other conditions: subject to the sale of another property, subject to council approval, or special conditions negotiated between the parties. Each condition will specify a due date, the party it protects, and the procedure for terminating or waiving under that clause.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timeline from exchange to unconditional</h2>
      <p>Once a contract is signed by both parties and dated, the conditional period begins. The due dates for each condition are measured from the contract date. A typical Brisbane residential contract might have a 14-day finance condition and a 7-day building and pest condition, meaning the contract could go unconditional around day 14 if all conditions are satisfied or waived by then.</p>

      <p>Finance approval periods have trended longer in recent years as lenders have applied more thorough assessment processes. In practice, 14 to 21 days is the common range for finance conditions, though some buyers with complex lending situations (self-employed borrowers, complex asset structures, unusual property types) will push for longer periods. Building and pest inspection windows are typically shorter, at 7 to 14 days, because the inspection itself can usually be arranged within two or three days of contract exchange.</p>

      <p>During the conditional period, both parties are nominally bound to proceed unless a condition gives one of them an exit right. From a seller's perspective, the practical effect is that the property is under contract but not yet sold. You cannot accept another offer to purchase during this period without being in breach of your own contract, but you have not yet achieved the certainty of an unconditional sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Satisfied versus waived: two paths to unconditional</h2>
      <p>A condition can be resolved in two ways. It can be satisfied, meaning the required event occurred (for example, the buyer received unconditional finance approval from their lender). Or it can be waived, meaning the party protected by the condition has chosen to proceed despite the condition not being formally satisfied or in the absence of completing the process the condition was designed to protect.</p>

      <p>Buyers sometimes waive a finance condition to strengthen their offer in a competitive market, accepting the risk that they proceed to settlement without the protection of that clause. This is a decision for the buyer to make with their own legal and financial advice. From a seller's perspective, a waived condition achieves the same outcome as a satisfied one: the contract is unconditional and the sale proceeds.</p>

      <p>Waivers and condition satisfaction both need to be communicated properly through the conveyancing process. Your solicitor or conveyancer will manage this, but it is worth understanding the mechanism so you are not left wondering when your sale is actually unconditional.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can and cannot do during the conditional period</h2>
      <p>Once a contract is signed, you are under contract. You cannot continue to market the property or accept another offer to purchase the same property during the conditional period. Your agent will typically advise any other interested buyers that the property is under contract, and that interest will need to be managed carefully in case the conditional contract falls through.</p>

      <p>What you can do is begin the steps that need to happen before settlement: instruct your solicitor or conveyancer to prepare the transfer documentation, gather the documents needed for settlement (rates and water clearance certificates, body corporate information if applicable), and in some cases begin the physical process of preparing to vacate if you have already found your next property.</p>

      <p>You cannot access the property for independent work or changes during the conditional period without the buyer's agreement, as they have a right to take possession of the property in the same condition as at contract date. Maintaining the property appropriately during this period is part of your obligations as vendor.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing the risk of a buyer terminating before unconditional</h2>
      <p>The practical reality of selling in Brisbane is that some conditional contracts do not proceed to unconditional. Finance approval is refused. A building inspection reveals something the buyer finds unacceptable. A buyer who waived a condition panics at the last moment and seeks legal advice about their exit options. These situations are uncommon in an active market with well-prepared properties, but they are not rare enough to be ignored.</p>

      <p>The two most reliable ways to reduce the risk of a conditional contract falling over are: pricing the property accurately so the lender's valuation supports the contract price (finance approvals most often fail because the lender's valuation comes in below the agreed price), and having the property properly prepared and presented so that a building and pest inspection does not produce a report that gives a nervous buyer a reason to exit.</p>

      <p>Your agent's role during the conditional period includes managing the buyer's expectations, staying in contact with the buyer's broker or lender where appropriate, and monitoring the progress of each condition as its due date approaches. An agent who is experienced in the Brisbane market will have a good sense of when a conditional contract is tracking well and when there are early signals that it may not proceed.</p>

